\begin_layout Standard
The research I will be presenting for my upcoming PhD defense is on the
 use of novel neutron detectors - Tensioned Metastable Fluid Detectors -
 in passive and active interrogation for special nuclear material interdiction.
 I've successfully implemented three different active interrogation methods
 with the detectors - differential die away analysis, interrogation of cargo
 for photofission, and threshold energy neutron analysis.
 The detectors - which I had a had a majority hand in designing the mechanical
 systems, electrical systems, writing of the firmware, and control software
 - recently won the best demo award at the 2016 IEEE Sensors conference.
 I have also received awards for the use of the data and filtering of the
 data from these systems, particularly the best paper at the 2016 American
 Nuclear Society Winter Meeting for my paper analyzing threshold energy
 neutron analysis for highly enriched uranium and the 2017 Innovations in
 Nuclear Technology R&D Award for the same methodology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before my current research, I performed more simulation and computational
 science work.
 I earned a 
