 concentration on my MSNE by developing a finite element model of our acoustical
ly run neutron detector.
 I developed a multiphysics model using the PDE solver COMSOL and verified
 the model using a laser based interrogation technique.
 I also was able to verify the thermoacoustics of the system - the sensitivity
 changes with temperature - and that has lead to much more robustness in
 the entire system.
 The work won me an award at the 2015 International Conference on Nuclear
 Engineering in Prague for my validation and verification technique of our
 detectors.
 Before that, I worked in a high performance computing environment at Argonne
 National Laboratory for a summer internship, using MC2 and VARIANT to validate
 fast reactor simulations.
 I was able to perform these computations on high performance computing
 resources, ultimately on Blue Gene P.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I also have experience working with real time controls in two regards.
 Recently, I developed a new methodology for detection of our neutron events.
 This method increased the timing resolution to the point that we could
 start to take acoustic spectrograms of the events.
 This capability so far has lead to the putative ability to discriminate
 alpha type events from neutron type events - an ability that can help in
 the detection of dark matter.
 I've also been able to develop a system for controlling the microsecond
 pulses of a DT neutron generator and sync this to our detector system,
 allowing for the ability to discriminate dangerous special nuclear material
 from inoccuous lowly enriched uranium.
 These are just two of the real time control systems I was able to develop
 during my graduate career.
\end_layout

